# Timeless SERP & social copy

## Default (no explicit user request)

- **Do not** put **time-sensitive** phrasing in `<title>`, `<meta name="description">`, **Open Graph `title` / `description`**, or **Twitter card** fields — e.g. “last reviewed January 2026”, “updated April 2026”, “as of 2026”, “new for 2026”, or any month/year that will go stale.
- **Do not** end meta descriptions with a **`…` ellipsis** or any **incomplete sentence** because of length. Stay within **165** characters with **full stops** (see `serp-metadata.mdc`). Titles: **≤ 70** characters total; **target ~65–70** including ` | FamiRelo` when keywords allow.
- **Do** write **evergreen, benefit-led** copy: intent + place + topic (family relocation, kids, schools, rent, visas where appropriate) so it stays accurate without maintenance.
- **Schema** may still use machine-readable `datePublished` / `dateModified` in JSON-LD from source data; that is not user-facing in the same way. Do not mirror those into visible meta strings unless asked.

## When the user *does* ask for freshness language

- Only then add review/update wording to titles, descriptions, or OG — and prefer **one** clear pattern (e.g. “Data updated [month]” in the **body** only if needed), not multiple inconsistent signals.

## Checklist

- [ ] No review month/year in `<title>`, meta description, or OG/Twitter `description` unless requested.
- [ ] Titles still respect `serp-metadata.mdc` (length, `FamiRelo` suffix, complete descriptions).
